# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1748-english-cricket-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] In **English cricket**, the earliest matches known to have involved the 2nd Duke of Richmond and Sir William Gage took place in the **1725 season**.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] The Artillery Ground in Finsbury, soon to become the sport's major venue, was mentioned in a cricketing context for the first time.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] However, the Honourable Artillery Company was expressing its disapproval of the ground being used for cricket.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] Richmond had written a letter to Gage in July, inviting him to form a team for a match to be played on the 20th.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] Gage's letter is archived in the West Sussex Record Office, on Orchard Street in Chichester.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] Other than the date and Gage's team having been defeated, nothing is known about the match on the 15th.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] Gage was a Member of Parliament who represented the former constituency of Seaford from 1722 until his death on 23 April 1744.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] The match on the 20th was to be played at Richmond's Goodwood estate, but the report in a *Daily Journal* newspaper on 21 July confirms Bury Hill (then called Berry Hill), near Arundel, as the venue.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] The teams are now known as the 2nd Duke of Richmond's XI and Sir William Gage's XI.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] The match, played before "a vast Concourse of People", was hosted by Thomas Howard, 8th Duke of Norfolk, who gave a ball at Arundel Castle in the evening.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] The newspaper said Richmond's XI "got the Victory above Forty, which was thought very much", and went on to praise the two teams as "the best that ever was seen to Play".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] The Honourable Artillery Company (HAC) had, in 1639, acquired the land in Finsbury that would become the Artillery Ground.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] Mr Robinson apparently took no notice of this and, on 7 October, proceedings were ordered to be taken against him for his neglect, and also for allowing cricket on the ground.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] A further note was added to the Court Minutes on 7 October concerning abuse done to the herbage of the ground by not only the horses but "also by Crickett Players".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] Despite HAC disapproval, the ground was being used for big matches only five years later.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] The earliest known match there was between Middlesex and Surrey on 10 August 1730.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] By 1725, cricket had been recorded in only eight English counties, although there had already been games in India and the Americas.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] In March 1725, American judge Samuel Sewall recorded instances of his lodger, Sam Hirst, playing cricket on common land in Boston.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] Sewall referred to the game as "wicket" and it had slight variations from English cricket.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] The pitch was longer at 25 yards (23 m) instead of 22 yards (20 m); the wickets were only four inches (ten centimetres) high and also much wider than in England.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] According to the *London Evening Post* on 27 March 1725, two men called Campbell and Marshall were arrested while they were playing cricket at Moorfields, north of London.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1725-english-cricket-season] They were charged with robbery, having mugged a courting couple a few days earlier in Islington.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] During the **1726 English cricket season**, a newspaper report named the players in a match, the first time this ever happened.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] The players concerned were Perry of London and Piper of Hampton, who played in what is the sport's earliest known single wicket match.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] In addition, brief reports of two eleven-a-side matches have survived.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] The main story of the year, as in some earlier seasons, concerns cricket's relationship with the law, and once again the issue was non-payment of gambling debts.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] County cricket was gaining in strength, and teams representing Kent and Surrey were prominent in 1726.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] By 1726, cricket had become an established sport in London and the south-eastern counties of England.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] It had also been played in India and North America by English colonists and sailors.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] The spread of cricket at home was limited by the constraints of travel at the time, but it was slowly gaining adherents in other parts of the country with references being found in counties outside the south-east, although it had apparently not reached the North of England yet.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] Having been essentially a rural pastime for well over a century, cricket was becoming a focus for wealthy patrons such as the 2nd Duke of Richmond; and also for gamblers whose interests would fund its growth through the 18th century.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] Other famous patrons in the 1720s were Edwin Stead of Kent; Sir William Gage of Sussex; and Alan Brodrick of Surrey.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] Gambling was prevalent at cricket matches in the Georgian era, and many gambling – or alcohol-fuelled incidents occurred.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] The issue was not addressed by the sport's ruling body until the 1770s, and it remained a significant factor even then.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] The counterpart of that was the reliance of cricket, as a professional sport, upon the investment accrued through gambling interests.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] No cricket had been reported in the infant newspaper industry before 1697 due to the Licensing of the Press Act 1662, which controlled the press until 1696.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] Reports were beginning to increase by the mid-1720s, though it would be a very long time before coverage became anything like comprehensive.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] The typical early report tended to be an advertisement for a scheduled match or else a brief discussion of the gambling odds, rather than the actual play, and it was not until 1726 that any player was mentioned by name in a newspaper report.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] The *London Evening Post* was founded in 1726 and carried a good many cricket notices until it ceased publication in 1797.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] The growth of the newspaper industry was important contemporarily for giving the sport much needed publicity, and historically for providing glimpses into a developing sport that had still not learned how to record itself for posterity.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] It was the *London Evening Post*, in its issue dated Saturday, 27 August 1726, that carried an advertisement for a single wicket match between players called "the noted Perry" (of London) and "the famous Piper" (of Hampton), playing for twenty pounds each.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] The match was played at Moulsey Hurst, a multi-sport venue near Molesey in Surrey.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] This is the first time that players are known to have been named in a newspaper, and the match itself is the earliest known to have been played under single wicket rules.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] Moulsey Hurst was especially famous for prizefighting, but it was often used for cricket throughout the 18th century.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] A feature of cricket in the 1720s was the increasing use by teams of county names.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] Teams called Kent and Surrey had been recorded as far back as 1709, though those may have been parish teams only.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] On 29 August 1726, a combined London & Surrey team hosted Stead's Kent on Kennington Common in a match classified as "important" by The Association of Cricket Statisticians and Historians (ACS).
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] The brief newspaper report said it was played "for 25 guineas between the men belonging to Edwin Stead, Esq. of Maidstone and the men of London and Surrey".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] Kent, based on the esteem of the Dartford club, and the successful patronage of Edwin Stead, is generally believed to have been the strongest county team in the 1720s.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] Cricket encountered some legal issues in the first quarter of the 18th century, including two court cases about unpaid gambling debts.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] The second of these followed a match in 1724 between Edwin Stead's XI and a Chingford team.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] Terminating Stead's lawsuit, Lord Chief Justice Pratt ordered the match "to be played out" on Dartford Brent in order that the stakes could be settled, but he died in 1725 before it was played out.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] The replay took place in September 1726 but, again, the result is unknown.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] In the same month and still on the subject of legal matters, a letter was written by a resident of Essex who complained that a local Justice of the Peace (JP) had seen fit to literally "read the Riot Act" to some people who were playing cricket on Saturday, 10 September.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] He had a constable with him who dispersed the players.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] Buckley commented that it seems the JP saw any game or sport as a pretence covering the gathering of disaffected people who intended to raise a rebellion.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] Given the ruling by Pratt, who had ordered the Stead v Chingford match to be played out on Dartford Brent, the issue raised by the letter-writer was that it was apparently lawful to play cricket in Kent, but not in Essex.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] One Surrey player who could well have been involved in the game at Kennington was Edmund Chapman of Chertsey, who died on Wednesday, 30 July 1763, aged 68.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] Chapman was an eminent master bricklayer, and "accounted one of the most dextrous cricket players in England".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1726-english-cricket-season] There are no known references to Chapman earlier than his obituary notice but, given his age, he must have been an active player from the 1710s until perhaps the 1730s, presumably playing for Chertsey, and possibly for Surrey, as his county team.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] In the **1727 English cricket season**, matches are, for the first time, known to have been played in accordance with agreed, written rules.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] Articles of Agreement were drawn up by the 2nd Duke of Richmond and Alan Brodrick, two of the sport's foremost patrons, to formalise the rules applicable to matches which they promoted.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] Details of four historically important matches have survived.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] The Articles of Agreement drawn up by the 2nd Duke of Richmond and Alan Brodrick may have been the first instance of rules being formally agreed, although rules as such definitely existed and, as in the early days of football, would have been agreed orally and subject to local variations.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] The Articles themselves are the source for two matches played earlier in the 1727 season by the 2nd Duke of Richmond's XI and Sir William Gage's XI.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] One of the written conditions is "the Duke of Richmond to choose any Gamesters, who have played in either of His Grace's two last Matches with Sir William Gage".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] Nothing else is known about the two Richmond v Gage matches.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] The first match between Richmond's XI and Alan Brodrick's XI was played in July, probably at Peper Harow, as the Articles state: "the first Match shall be played some day of this instant July in the county of Surry".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] Brodrick to choose any Gamesters within three Miles of Pepperhara (*sic*), provided they actually lived there last Lady Day".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] Peper Harow is about four miles from Godalming, and was the home of the Brodrick family.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] There is a view that it was the venue of the match in July.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] The Articles then state: "the second match to be played in August next in the County of Sussex, the Place to be named by the Duke of Richmond".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] Thomas Waymark is the only player mentioned in connection with either match.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] Accounted the first great all-rounder, Waymark played for over 20 years and was noted for his "extraordinary agility and dexterity".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] Horace Walpole commented that cricket was already "common" at Eton College.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] This is the earliest reference to cricket being played both at Eton, and in the county of Berkshire.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] A match was played at Cranbrook, Kent on Monday, 29 May between "14 old men of that town".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] The match was to celebrate Restoration Day, also known as Oak Apple Day.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] There was a game on Warehorne Green, at Warehorne in Kent, on Monday, 5 June that was arranged by George Baker, Esq. who is described as the General Receiver; and Thomas Hodges, Esq.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1727-english-cricket-season] The teams were Warehorne v Hawkshurst, and they played twelve-a-side.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] In the **1728 English cricket season**, it is possible to discern the existence of an inter-county rivalry between teams representative of Kent and Sussex.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] Details of four historically important matches are known.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] A Swiss traveller in southern England recorded county cricket as "a commonplace" and wrote that it unites "the common people and men of rank".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] Teams of county strength were being formed as the patrons sought stronger combinations to help them in the serious, for them, business of winning wagers.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] Easily the most successful in 1728 was Edwin Stead whose Kent was "too expert" for Sussex, led by the 2nd Duke of Richmond and Sir William Gage.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] There were three matches between teams which were potentially representative of Kent and Sussex.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] Nominally, however, the Kent team was Edwin Stead's XI, while the Sussex team in the first two matches was the 2nd Duke of Richmond's XI, and Sir William Gage's XI in the third.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] The first match was on Coxheath Common, then called Cock's Heath, on 25 June, pre-announced in the *Kentish Weekly Post* on 19 June.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] They played a return match at Penshurst Park sometime in July; this one was the subject of a brief notice in the *Whitehall Evening Post* dated 6 August 1728.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] Reports of the third match, played at Penshurst Park in either late July or early August, state that it was "the third time this summer that the Kent men have been too expert for those of Sussex".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] The 6 August editions of both the *London Evening Post* and the *Daily Journal* include the "too expert" comment, and so modern sources agree that Stead's XI won both of the matches against Richmond's XI.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] The third match between Stead's XI and Gage's XI was for a stake of 50 guineas.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] It was hosted by John Sidney, 6th Earl of Leicester, at Penshurst Park.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] Stead's XI won by 7 runs – the newspaper report says "the former [Gage's XI] wanted 7 to be even with (them)".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] The proclamation of Kent's superiority in 1728 is the first time that the concept of a "champion county" can be seen in the sources, and it was augmented by a "turned the scales" comment made by a reporter after Sussex defeated Kent in 1729.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] The 1729 report added that the "scale of victory had been on the Kentish team for some years past".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] In 1730, a newspaper referred to the "Kentish champions".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] There was a match in August between Richmond's XI and Gage's XI.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] The sources say the teams "met again" but it is not clear if they had already played each other in 1728; they had met in earlier seasons.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] The match was at an unspecified venue in Lewes and the result is unknown.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] Swiss traveller César-François de Saussure noted in his journal the frequency with which he saw cricket being played while he was making his journeys across southern England in June.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] He referred to county matches as "a commonplace" and wrote that "everyone plays it, the common people and also men of rank".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] In several sources, a Gentlemen of Middlesex v Gentlemen of London match is listed as due to take place in Islington on Tuesday (*sic*), 5 August.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] In fact, 5 August 1728 was a Monday, and recent research has confirmed that the match in question was due to be held on Tuesday, 5 August 1729.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] The archives at Goodwood House, Richmond's seat, include numerous receipts for purchases made by the Duke in 1728 which relate to his cricketing interests.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] Three are from a tradesman called Walter Seagar for "binding bats at Lyndhurst", the amounts ranging from 2 to 4 shillings.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] Another, dated 21 June, is for "11 pairs of men's thread hose for ye gentlemen Crickett players" amounting to £2 9s 6d.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1728-english-cricket-season] Also, in an undated accounting entry, the Duke paid 12 shillings each for "twelve yellow velvet caps with silver tassells", which is understood to have been his team colours.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] There are signs of increasing media interest in the **1729 English cricket season** as reports of seven historically important matches have survived, compared with four in each of the two previous years.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] Although the source information is confusing, Sir William Gage's XI achieved the earliest known innings victory when they defeated Edwin Stead's XI at Penshurst Park in August.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] The best of the known professional players at this time was the all-rounder Thomas Waymark, who was a groom employed by the 2nd Duke of Richmond.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] Cricket continued to spread throughout England, and is known to have reached both Gloucestershire and Norfolk in 1729; also, its popularity at the University of Oxford was attested by Dr Samuel Johnson, a student there at the time.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] The oldest known bat, now on display in the Kennington Oval pavilion, is dated 1729.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] Dartford and London played each other twice in 1729.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] The first match, on 30 July, was played in Dartford—probably on Dartford Brent.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] The stake was £50 but the result of the match is unknown.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] This match is mentioned in correspondence to the 4 September 1890 edition of *Cricket: A Weekly Record of the Game*.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] There were two matches in which both teams were named after their respective counties.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] However, there is no certainty at this stage of cricket's development that any team was representative of a whole county.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] It has been suggested that teams called Kent, for example, consisted of players from the Dartford area only.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] Kent played in both matches, one against Sussex and the other against Surrey.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] Kent played Sussex 24 June on Walworth Common, a neutral venue in Surrey which was used occasionally during this period.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] The *London Evening Post* pre-announced: "On Tuesday next at Walworth Common will be play'd a Match at Cricket between the Counties of Kent and Sussex, for fifty Pounds a side, to meet at One o'Clock, play or pay".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] That is a typical example of an eighteenth century notice.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] This one is unusual, however, in its emphasis upon county names, rather than some other nomenclature, and it is notable as the earliest mention of a team expressly called Sussex, though teams of similar strength had been raised by Sussex patrons in earlier seasons.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] The 26 August edition of the *Daily Journal* reported that a match would be played same day near Farnham between "Mr Steed (*sic*) of Kent and his Company, against the best Players in the County of Surrey".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] Farnham was later known for its Holt Pound ground that was associated with Billy Beldham and John Wells.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] Edwin Stead of Kent again matched his team against those of his Sussex rivals, the 2nd Duke of Richmond and Sir William Gage.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] As a newspaper report said, "the scale of victory (for some years past) has been generally on the Kentish side".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] But, on 28 August, when Stead's XI met Gage's XI at Penshurst Park, Gage's team is believed to have gained the earliest known innings victory (i.e., scoring more in one completed innings than their opponents in two).
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] It is understood that Stead's XI were all players from Kent, but Gage's XI included players from Hampshire and Surrey as well as Sussex, and is also known as Hampshire, Surrey & Sussex.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] The match was played for 100 guineas with "some thousands" watching.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] The newspaper says Gage's XI "got as many within 3 in one Hand, as the former did in two, so the Kentish men flung it up".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] A "hand" was a team's innings but the report is confusing because Stead's XI must have batted last and they apparently conceded the match when still three runs behind—therefore Gage's XI won by an innings and three runs.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] Thomas Waymark, described as "a groom of the Duke of Richmond" was the outstanding player.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] The report says he "signalised himself by extraordinary agility and dexterity" and "turned the scale of victory".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] There was a return match in September on "The Downs" near Lewes.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] A report in the *British Journal* on 13 September says: "The great match played at Penshurst will be played again in Sussex".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] As before, it was effectively Kent against a team from three counties.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] Ashley-Cooper asserted that the three counties team should have been called England, even though cricket at that time had still not made headway beyond its native southeast.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] Cricket continued to spread throughout England, and a local game in Gloucester on 22 September 1729 is the earliest known reference to cricket in the county of Gloucestershire.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] The match was pre-announced 15 September in the *Gloucester Journal* which said the prize was "upwards of 20 guineas".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] There has been confusion over a pre-announced match on Tuesday, 5 August 1729.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] Waghorn's original research, he noted the date as Tuesday, 5 August 1728, and several sources have subsequently listed the match in 1728.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] A review of the primary source confirmed that the match in question was due to be held on Tuesday, 5 August 1729.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] The given day of the week did not match the calendar, because 5 August 1728 was a Monday.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] The teams were the Gentlemen of Middlesex and the Gentlemen of London; they were due to meet "in the Field behind the *Woolpack* Back Gate near Sadler's Wells" for a stake of £50 per side.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] It is not known if the match was actually played, but it is the earliest known to involve teams using "Gentlemen" in their name, and it was also the first in which a team is called Middlesex.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] "Gentlemen only" matches did not involve professionals, and are not as highly rated as those that did, especially so on this occasion as the London club's first team was playing Dartford on the same day (see § Dartford v London).
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] There is a bat in the Kennington Oval pavilion which belonged to John Chitty of Knaphill, Surrey.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] It looks more like a field hockey stick than a modern cricket bat, but its curvature was to enable the batsman to play a ball that was always rolled or skimmed along the ground, as in bowls, never pitched.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] Pitching began about 30 years later, and the straight bats used nowadays were invented in response to the pitched delivery.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] Although matches in the county of Norfolk are unknown before 1745, the *Norwich Gazette* and the *Norwich Mercury* both carried notices for the Gage/Stead match in September 1729.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] Dr Samuel Johnson attended the University of Oxford from October 1728 until the following summer, and later told James Boswell that cricket matches were played there.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1729-english-cricket-season] Boswell mentioned this in his *Life of Samuel Johnson*.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] The most noticeable aspect of the **1730 English cricket season** is the largest number of matches on record to date, with much more coverage in the newspapers than in all previous seasons.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] Significantly, the surviving reports show the growing importance of the sport in metropolitan London and its surrounding areas.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] The Artillery Ground entered the historical record for the first time while London Cricket Club established its prominence.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] The club's rivals tended to be county teams with Kent, Middlesex, Surrey, and Sussex all active.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] Details of twenty historically important matches are known.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] In Sussex, the cricketing rivalry between Charles Lennox, 2nd Duke of Richmond and Sir William Gage was set to continue and at least two matches were arranged.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] However, it is not certain if either were played and one was certainly "put off".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] In a letter written by one Henry Forster on 10 June, he says (*sic*): "Ye say in Chichester his grace [Richmond] is to play a cricket mach friday [12 June] with Sr Willm Gaige on Bery Hill".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] Richmond's XI and Gage's XI were due to play again 5 August at The Dripping Pan in Lewes, but the match "was put off on account of (Thomas) Waymark, the Duke's man, being ill".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] It is not clear if it was cancelled or postponed.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] The Dripping Pan is a grassy-banked natural amphitheatre off Mountfield Road in Lewes; it is today the home of Lewes F.C.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] In the sense of both teams being labelled with the names of counties, there were four "inter-county" matches, but 18th century nomenclature should never be taken literally as a team called, say, Sussex might mean nothing more than the fact that its patron lived in that county.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] Surrey defeated Middlesex 2–4 July on Richmond Green, and Sussex 9 July on Merrow Down, Guildford—in both matches, the margin of victory is unknown.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] Surrey played Middlesex again on 10 August and this time Middlesex won.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] That match is the earliest known to have been played on the Artillery Ground, in Finsbury.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] A third match was proposed as "the Surrey gentlemen are very desirous of saving their credit if possible".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] A provisional date of 17 August was set but there was no mention of a venue.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] Kent, under its patron Edwin Stead, seems to have been the strongest county team.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] The *St James Evening Post* on 8 August reported: "'Twas thought that the Kentish champions would have lost their honours by being beat at one innings if time had permitted".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] The match in question was played 5 August in Blackheath against London, whose team often opposed counties, and the wording of the report suggests that the result was cricket's earliest known draw.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] It is also the first time that a team was called the "champions", while "losing their honours" suggests the loss of a title, though no titles of any kind were officially recognised at the time.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] The reference to 'innings' in the report is the earliest on record.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] In all, Kent played three matches against London.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] The first was on 2 July at a venue in the Gray's Inn area, and Kent won that by an unknown margin.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] The precise location was "a field near the lower end of Gray's Inn Lane, London".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] The newspaper reported "a cricket-match between the Kentish men and the Londoners for £50, and won by the former".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] The second match was the probable draw on 5 August, and they played a third match 12 August at Frog Lane in Islington but, as the newspaper reported: "being obliged by their articles to leave off at seven o’clock, they could not finish it".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] London had a lead of 30 when play ended, and it was agreed to resume 18 August on Kennington Common, but the final result is unknown.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] Surrey also played three matches against London.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] The first was played 17 August on Kennington Common, the others 31 August and 4 September on the Artillery Ground.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] London won the first two by margins of one run and six runs respectively; the result of the third match is unknown.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] A brief report of the match on Kennington Common says it was "thought to be one of the completest matches that ever was played".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] Reports of four single wicket matches have been found.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] Three of these appear to have been a series between Four of Kent and Four of Brentford.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] The first two were played for a stake of £50 and the third, perhaps a decider, "for a considerable wager".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] The first match was played 28 May on Westerham Common, "articles being drawn to play or pay", and this was followed by a return on 4 June at Kew Green—neither result is known.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] The third match did not take place until 26 August on Walworth Common and Four of Brentford won it.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] On 29 June, there was a "two threes" single wicket match for £50 at Mickleham Downs between Three of Surrey and Three of Sussex.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] A report in the *London Evening Post* says the players were "esteemed the best in the respective counties", but does not name them.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] During April, there were reports in a number of journals about the 2nd Duke of Richmond and other members of the nobility playing cricket in Hyde Park.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] One such report on 7 April stated: "His Grace the Duke of Richmond, and several other young Noblemen and gentlemen, have begun to divert themselves each Morning at the Play of Cricket in Hide (*sic*) Park, and design to pursue that wholesome Exercise every fair Morning during the Spring".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] A report on 25 April anticipated a match for 100 guineas, but no further details have been found.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] In July, Surrey's patron for their match against Sussex was a Mr Andrews.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] It is known that he was a resident of Sunbury-on-Thames.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] Evidence of how cricket was gaining media coverage is apparent in reports of local matches on 9 and 13 July.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] The first, "for a guinea a man" was a single wicket match won by three players from Hawkhurst.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] The second was between a "gentlemen only" team and the so-called "Lumbar Troop"—the result is unknown.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] On 23 July, Epsom played Sunbury on Epsom Down, but no details are known.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] Greenwich Cricket Club played London in Blackheath on 31 July, but the stake was relatively low at 20 guineas and London may not have sent their strongest team.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] A twelve-a-side game was played 17 August at Tonbridge and "backed by a great many of the noblemen and gentry of that place".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] It seems to have been a tight contest which was unfinished on the day, so another date was chosen for the conclusion, but nothing further is known.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] On 9 September, there was a match on Putney Heath between Putney and Fulham for a stake of 50 guineas.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] It is the only known instance of a team called Putney and of a match at this venue, which is now part of Wimbledon Common.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1730-english-cricket-season] A match played 2 October on Datchet Heath, near Windsor, is the first reference to cricket in the county of Buckinghamshire.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] In the **1731 English cricket season**, a total of 31 historically important matches are known to have been arranged, more than double the number in 1730, though it is not certain they were all actually played.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Seventeen involved the London Cricket Club, who played six of their twelve home games on the Artillery Ground in Finsbury.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Although newspaper coverage was increasing, the notices carried were always brief, and it remained rare for a player to be named in the press.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] However, this did happen when "the famous Tim Coleman", of London, was mentioned after he played for another team as a given man.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] The most controversial match of the season, which ended in a riot, was also the first from which team totals are known.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Elsewhere, the Prince of Wales is known to have taken an interest in the sport, and he became a noted patron until his death in 1751.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] The match was the third, possibly a decider, played between these two teams who had met on each of the two previous Mondays—the first was at Richmond Green on the 9th (result unknown) with a return at Chichester on the 16th (Chambers won).
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] The start and finish times, specified in the Articles, were two pm and seven pm.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Richmond and his team arrived late, so start of play was delayed.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Evidently, the large crowd expected the lost time to be added on at the end.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Richmond, whose team were losing, insisted on ending the match as soon as the clock struck seven.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] The gambling odds were on Chambers, and his backers were furious that Lennox would not play on, so they rioted.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] The match is significant in another aspect because it is the earliest of which team totals are known, though no individual scores were recorded.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Richmond's XI batted first and were all out for 79, to which Chambers' XI replied with 119 for a first innings lead of 40.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Richmond's XI were dismissed for 72 in their second innings, leaving Chambers' XI with a target of 33 to win.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Their precise total at the end is uncertain, but the wording of the report suggests they had scored from 23 to 25 runs for the loss of five or six wickets.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] During the riot, some of Richmond's players had "the shirts torn off their backs", and one report said "a law suit would commence about the play".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] However, the brief report of a different match on 6 September implied that Richmond had conceded the result to Chambers: "11 of Surrey beat the 11 who about a fortnight ago beat the Duke of Richmond's men".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Teams that were nominally counties took part in ten matches altogether.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Nomenclature at this time was indefinite, so a team called Kent or Surrey might actually have been Dartford or Chertsey, for example.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] London Cricket Club played four matches against teams with county names: Kent on 24 May (Kent won by 3 runs) and 8 June (London won); Surrey on 17 April (London won by 35 runs) and 28 September (result unknown).
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Surrey defeated Thomas Chambers' XI on 6 September, as mentioned above, and played two other matches against parish teams; Kent also played one against parish opposition.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Only two matches were "inter-county", inasmuch as both teams had county names.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] These were Kent v Middlesex at Kennington Common on 19 July, and Surrey v Kent at Dulwich Common on 4 September.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] The Kent v Middlesex match was billed in advance as "the County of Kent v. the County of Middlesex, for £50 a side", but the result is unknown.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] In the second match, Surrey in their second innings needed twelve to win with three wickets in hand when heavy rain began, and the result was a draw.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] In addition to their matches against county teams, London played five against Dartford Cricket Club, and four against Croydon.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] All of London's home games were played on the Artillery Ground; Dartford played on Dartford Brent, and Croydon at Duppas Hill.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Little is known of these nine matches except, mostly, the results.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Croydon won all four of their matches against London, including the fourth which counted as a replay following a dispute about the outcome of the third.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] London had some success against Dartford, winning the first match on the Artillery Ground by 15 runs.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Two of the other matches were drawn, and two left no result.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Only one single wicket match is in the known records.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] It was played in July, at a venue in Maidstone, between two Royal Horse Guards officers called Captain Beak and Lieutenant Coke.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] The brief report said "a considerable sum of money" was at stake, and Beak won after three hours "very hard played".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Waghorn, who remarked that it was the first "military match" he found in his researches.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Nothing is known about the playing standards of Beak or Coke, or if either of them played for Kent or another county, but many Army officers did play in important matches through the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Two examples were Colonel Charles Lennox (1764–1819) and Captain Charles Cumberland (1764–1835), both members of the White Conduit Club and, in 1787, original members of Marylebone Cricket Club (MCC).
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Colonel Lennox became the 4th Duke of Richmond in 1806, and was the 2nd Duke's grandson.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] The earliest known ground enclosures were done this year.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] The playing area on Kennington Common was roped off twice in an attempt to keep spectators off the field.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] A notice for the London v Sevenoaks match on 12 July said the ground would be roped around, and all persons must stay outside of it.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] Surrey v London on 28 September was promoted as "likely to be the best performance of this kind that has been seen for some time, there being great wagers depending", and the Prince of Wales was expected to attend.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] The notice also stated: "for the convenience of the gamesters, the ground is to be staked and roped out".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] It is not known when admission fees were introduced but there was certainly a two pence charge in place at the Artillery Ground by the early 1740s.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] In July (exact date unknown), there was an unusual match at Duppas Hill, Croydon, when a Kent team played a Surrey team who were all called Wood.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1731-english-cricket-season] This is interesting given the well-documented confusion over different players called Wood or Woods in the 1770s.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] The **1748 English cricket season** was the zenith of single wicket, never so popular before or since.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] A total of 18 significant single wicket matches are in the records, compared with a mere handful of eleven-a-side games.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] 1748 was the zenith of single wicket, and numerous matches were organised from June to September.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] On an unknown date early in the month, Tom Faulkner defeated Robert Colchin by one wicket.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Colchin scored 40 and 5; Faulkner scored 45 and 1*.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] A "fives" game on Monday, 5 June took place on the Artillery Ground between Addington and The Rest, excluding Kent.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Addington's players were Tom Faulkner, Joe Harris, John Harris, George Jackson, and William Durling (described as "the shoemaker that lately came out of Kent").
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Their opponents were Stephen Dingate, Little Bennett, Maynard, Collins, and Thomas Waymark.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] This appears to be the first time that a team specifically called "The Rest" was ever assembled.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Three "servants of the Duke of Richmond" played Three of London at the Artillery Ground on Friday, 24 June.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] The result is unknown but the match started quite late at four o'clock.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Richmond's team was Stephen Dingate, Joseph Rudd, and Pye; London's three were Little and Tall Bennett, and William Anderson.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] The match was reported in the *London Evening Post* on Saturday, 25 June.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] On Saturday, 25 June a return match between Colchin and Faulkner took place on Addington Hill.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] He made 7 and 12; Faulkner replied with 11 and 6.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] A third game between Colchin and Faulkner, "each having previously won one", was held on the Artillery Ground, Monday 4 July.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Unfortunately, there are no match details this time.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] On the same day, also on the Artillery Ground, Thomas Waymark and Darville played as Two of Berkshire against Little Bennett and George Smith of London.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Smith was allowed an unnamed substitute in the field.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Darville was the owner of Bray Mills, where Waymark worked at this time.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Smith, apparently having resolved his financial problems, was still the landlord of the famous *Py'd Horse* and keeper of the Artillery Ground.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] A "fives" match was played Wednesday, 6 July on the Artillery Ground.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Tom Faulkner's Side beat Stephen Dingate's Side by one wicket.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Two runs were required when the last man went in.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] The teams were: Tom Faulkner, Joe Harris, William Anderson, and Little and Tall Bennett versus Stephen Dingate, Joseph Rudd, Pye, James Bryant, and John Bryant.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] The same two teams of "fives" met again from Wednesday, 13 to Friday, 15 July.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] This match was also on the Artillery Ground.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Play was interrupted by rain on the Wednesday after one team had completed its first innings, scoring 13.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] No further details are known but, as an apparent "decider" was played on Wednesday, 27 July, perhaps Dingate's team won this one.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] On Wednesday, 27 July, there was another "fives" game between the Faulkner and Dingate teams on the Artillery Ground.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] This match may have been a decider; in which case Dingate's team must have won the second match on Friday, 15 July.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] The teams were not the same as before: Dingate, Richard Newland, Joseph Rudd, Maynard (of Surrey), and Little Bennett played against Faulkner, Joe Harris, William Durling (of Addington), James and John Bryant.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] The Artillery Ground staged two matches on Monday, 8 August.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] First, Tom Faulkner and Joe Harris played Robert Colchin and Val Romney at "twos" for twenty guineas a side.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Immediately afterwards, there was the return of the Waymark/Darville versus Bennett/Smith game, with Smith again allowed a substitute fielder.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] A "fives" game was played Saturday, 20 August on the Artillery Ground.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] The teams were: Robert Colchin, John Colchin, James Bryant, John Bryant, and Robert Lascoe against Joe Harris, Maynard, John Capon, William Anderson, and Walker.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] This is the only known mention of the player called Walker.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] On Monday, 22 August, a "fives" game was played on the Artillery Ground for 20 guineas a side between Five of Berkshire and Five of London.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Berkshire's team was Thomas Waymark, Darville, and three others.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] The London players were William Anderson, Little and Tall Bennett, John Capon, and George Carter.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Tom Faulkner's Five defeated Long Robin's Five on Monday, 29 August, by four runs.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] The match was played at the Artillery Ground for a prize of £200.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Val Romney was badly injured and could not run but, the rules being *play or pay*, he was obliged to play as well as he could.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] The teams were Faulkner, Joe Harris, James Bryant, John Bryant, and William Durling against Colchin, Romney, Maynard, John Larkin, and Jones.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] There were four known matches this month, all of them played on the Artillery Ground.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] On Monday, 5 September, there was an odds match between Three of England and Five of Berkshire for 20 guineas.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] The teams were Robert Colchin, Tom Faulkner, and George Smith against Thomas Waymark and four others of Berkshire.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] George Smith was not allowed a substitute (termed a "Seeker-out" in the primary source) as in previous games, and had to do his share of the fielding.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] On Friday, 16 September, Colchin and Waymark teamed up to defeat Faulkner and Joe Harris.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] It was announced beforehand that "in case of rain, there is good shelter for the spectators".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Apparently, the match gave such great satisfaction that an immediate return was arranged.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Colchin & Waymark scored 10 and 17, against 0 and 15.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] In their first innings, Faulkner and Harris were both bowled second ball.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Details were reported in the *London Evening Post* on Saturday, 17 September.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] The return was played next day for fifty guineas.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Colchin and Waymark again defeated Faulkner and Joe Harris.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Finally, a "threes" game was played Friday, 23 September "for a considerable sum".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Colchin, Waymark, and Maynard met Faulkner, Joe Harris, and John Bryant.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Two Kent v England matches were played 10 and 13 June on Dartford Brent and the Artillery Ground respectively.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Kent won the first by 11 runs, and the second by an unknown margin.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] London defeated Lambeth 14 June on Peckham Rye Common, as reported by the *Whitehall Evening Post* on Thursday, 16 June.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] London also played against Croydon on 18 July, and Deptford & Greenwich on 15 August.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Both matches were on the Artillery Ground, but the results are unknown.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] On 23 August, Deptford & Greenwich hosted London on "Mr Siddle's new cricket-ground at Deptford".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] George Smith, keeper of the Artillery Ground and landlord of the adjoining *Pyed Horse* in Chiswell Street, declared bankruptcy.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] Evidently his pricing problems of recent years did have some basis in needing to balance the books after all.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] A number of notices appeared in the press during the first six months of 1748 but Smith eventually resolved his problems, perhaps through the sale of other property, and was able to retain control of the Artillery Ground until 1752.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] There was a game played 4 August on Coxheath Common between teams representing "the Hill" and "the Valley".
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] This sounds like a similar idea to the early match at Chevening in the year 1610; and may have been commemorative.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] In 1748, an action of Jeffreys v Parsons was heard before the King's Bench.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] The case concerned wagers that were almost certainly made on the above two Kent v England games, with Jeffreys claiming 25 guineas won from Parsons on each game.
[src:1748-english-cricket-season/1748-english-cricket-season] The parties came to an out of court agreement after the case was held over.
